content.problemStatement:
A **while loop with continue** allows skipping specific iterations of the loop based on a condition. The `continue` statement forces the loop to **immediately move to the next iteration** without executing the remaining code in the current iteration.  

This is useful when you need to **skip certain values** while processing a series of inputs, filtering data, or handling conditions dynamically.  


**Syntax:**
```java
while (condition) {  
    // Code before continue  
    if (skipCondition) {  
        continue; // Skip to the next iteration  
    }  
    // Code after continue (will be skipped if condition is met)  
}
```
---

**Examples:**

```java
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int i = 1; // Initialize counter

        while (i <= 5) { // Loop from 1 to 5
            if (i == 3) { // Check if the number is 3
                i++; // Increment before skipping
                continue; // Skip this iteration
            }
            System.out.println(i); // Print the number
            i++; // Move to the next number
        }
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**  
```default
1  
2  
4  
5  
```

